## Commands

```bash
# Generate from spec
penguiflow generate --spec {{ agent_name }}.yaml

# Validate spec without generating
penguiflow generate --spec {{ agent_name }}.yaml --dry-run

# Force regenerate (danger: overwrites existing files, including tool/flow implementations)
# Use only on a clean working tree, or after committing/stashing your changes.
penguiflow generate --spec {{ agent_name }}.yaml --force

# Run the agent
uv run python -m {{ package_name }} "Your query"

# Run tests
uv run pytest
```

---

## Generated vs Developer-Owned Files

### Spec-synced (always regenerated; do not edit)

- `src/{{ package_name }}/planner.py`
- `src/{{ package_name }}/config.py`
- `src/{{ package_name }}/tools/__init__.py`
- `src/{{ package_name }}/flows/__init__.py`
- `src/{{ package_name }}/*_orchestrator.py` (flow orchestrators, if any)
- `README.md`
- `.env.example`
- `ENV_SETUP.md`
- `tests/conftest.py`

### Scaffolds (created when missing; safe to modify)

- `src/{{ package_name }}/tools/*.py` (tool implementations)
- `src/{{ package_name }}/flows/*.py` (flow implementations)
- `tests/test_tools/test_*.py` and `tests/test_flows/test_*.py`
- `src/{{ package_name }}/orchestrator.py` (entrypoint wiring)
- `.env` (your local secrets)

### Notes
- If a scaffold exists, it will not be overwritten unless you pass `--force` (or delete the file first).
- Keep custom code in separate modules and have scaffolds call into them; this makes regeneration safer.

